Linear regression and sample size

Peter Ralph

Sun Sep 12 07:13:15 2021

Wed like to know how accurately we can estimate the slope of a linear relationship as a function of sample size.

Oh, and were stuck on a desert island with no internet access or statistics books and we forgot all our math.

So, lets find out by simulation!

One data set

Lets simulate some samples, fit a linear model, and make a plot just to check everything looks right.

Simulated data:

n <- 10
slope <- 0.2
noise.sd <- 0.25
xy <- data.frame( x=rnorm(n))
xy$y <- xy$x * slope + noise.sd*rnorm(n)
summary(xy)
##        x                 y           
##  Min.   :-0.6688   Min.   :-0.45867  
##  1st Qu.:-0.3222   1st Qu.: 0.09782  
##  Median : 0.1898   Median : 0.17538  
##  Mean   : 0.3947   Mean   : 0.17274  
##  3rd Qu.: 0.5177   3rd Qu.: 0.35906  
##  Max.   : 2.5266   Max.   : 0.68195

Now, fit a linear model:

xy.lm <- lm( y ~ x, data=xy )
summary(xy.lm)

Look at the results:

plot( y ~ x, data=xy )
abline(coef(xy.lm),col='red')

Many data sets:

Wed like to do the above many times for a given sample size.

n <- 10
slope <- 0.2
noise.sd <- 0.25
nreps <- 1000
many.lms <- replicate( nreps, {
        xy <- data.frame( x=rnorm(n))
        xy$y <- xy$x * slope + noise.sd*rnorm(n)
        xy.lm <- lm( y ~ x, data=xy )
        return( coef(xy.lm) )
    } )
# hist the intercept and slope
layout(t(1:2))
hist( many.lms[1,], main="intercept" )
hist( many.lms[2,], main="slope" )

Lets just look at a bunch of those lines, for fun:

plot(0,type='n',xlab='',ylab='',xlim=c(-1,1),ylim=c(-1,1))
for (k in 1:100) {
    abline( many.lms[1,k], many.lms[2,k], col=adjustcolor("black",0.1) )
}

Systematic comparison

First thing: make a function.

sim.many.lms <- function (n, nreps=1000) {
    many.lms <- replicate( nreps, {
            xy <- data.frame( x=rnorm(n))
            xy$y <- xy$x * slope + noise.sd*rnorm(n)
            xy.lm <- lm( y ~ x, data=xy )
            return( coef(xy.lm) )
        } )
}

Now, apply it to the sample sizes of interest:

n.vals <- floor(seq(10,500,length.out=10))
sim.lms <- lapply( n.vals, sim.many.lms )
layout(t(1:2))
for (k in seq_along(n.vals)) {
    hist(sim.lms[[k]][1,], main=paste("intercepts, n=",n.vals[k]))
    hist(sim.lms[[k]][2,], main=paste("slopes, n=",n.vals[k]))
}

OK, lets summarize the results on slope:

layout(t(1:2))
boxplot( lapply( sim.lms, function (x) x[2,] ), names=n.vals )
plot(n.vals, sapply( sim.lms, function (x) sd(x[2,]) ), ylab="SD of slope" )
